### Description

This issue bases off the discussion in #37229.

`createInjector` is useful to statically inject providers from lazy-loaded modules. My specific use case is validating my routing config which references lazy-loaded modules.

In [this](https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/37229#issuecomment-881769914) comment, @alxhub mentioned that the function is exposed via `Injector.create`, which is only half-true since only the module name to the function, stripping it from its providers and imports:
```ts
  // https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/core/src/di/injector.ts#L110
  static create(
      options: StaticProvider[]|{providers: StaticProvider[], parent?: Injector, name?: string},
      parent?: Injector): Injector {
    if (Array.isArray(options)) {
      return createInjector({name: ''}, parent, options, '');
    } else {
      const name = options.name ?? '';
      return createInjector({name}, options.parent, options.providers, name);
    }
  }
```

### Proposed solution

An overload for `Injector.create` should be added which accepts a module definition and returns its injector, just like the private `createInjector` does.

### Alternatives considered

For now I'll have to use the private `ÉµcreateInjector`.

